            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the day of week calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This day of week calculator uses a variant of
                <strong>Zeller’s congruence</strong> to convert any date into a
                weekday index (0–6) and then maps that index to Monday–Sunday.
                The algorithm is purely arithmetic and does not rely on built-in
                browser date functions, which makes it predictable and easy to
                explain.
              </p>

              <h3>The core idea</h3>
              <p>
                Every date can be represented as an offset from a known
                reference date. If you know that 1 January 2000 was a Saturday,
                and you know how many days separate your date from that
                reference, you can compute the weekday by taking the remainder
                when dividing by 7.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Conceptually:</p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >weekdayIndex = (referenceWeekday + daysDifference) mod
                    7</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  where <code>weekdayIndex</code> is 0–6 and maps to
                  Monday–Sunday (or Sunday–Saturday, depending on convention).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Zeller’s congruence (Gregorian calendar)</h3>
              <p>
                One popular formula for Gregorian dates is Zeller’s congruence.
                For a date with day <code>d</code>, month <code>m</code>, and
                year <code>y</code>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  If month is January or February, treat them as month 13 or 14
                  of the previous year:
                </p>
                <pre><code>if m = 1 or 2:
  m = m + 12
  y = y - 1</code></pre>
                <p class="mt-2">Then compute:</p>
                <pre><code>h = (d + ⌊13(m + 1) / 5⌋ + K + ⌊K / 4⌋ + ⌊J / 4⌋ + 5J) mod 7</code></pre>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><code>K = y mod 100</code> (year of the century)</li>
                  <li><code>J = ⌊y / 100⌋</code> (zero-based century)</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  In this formulation, <code>h = 0</code> means Saturday,
                  <code>1</code> Sunday, <code>2</code> Monday, …,
                  <code>6</code> Friday. The calculator internally converts this
                  to a Monday–Sunday index for display.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Gregorian vs. Julian dates</h2>
              <p>
                The <strong>Gregorian calendar</strong> is the modern calendar
                used by most of the world today. It was introduced in 1582 to
                correct drift in the older <strong>Julian calendar</strong>.
                Different countries adopted the Gregorian calendar at different
                times, sometimes skipping several days in the process.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Gregorian (modern):</strong> Use this for almost all
                  contemporary dates and most planning tasks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Julian (historical):</strong> Use this if you are
                  working with historical documents that explicitly reference
                  Julian dates (for example, some dates before 1700 in Europe).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator lets you choose which system to apply so you can
                match the convention used in your source material.
              </p>

              <h2>Interpreting the “difference from today”</h2>
              <p>
                The “difference from today” line shows how many days separate
                your chosen date from the current local date:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>0 days:</strong> the date is today.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Positive:</strong> the date is in the future (e.g.,
                  “in 42 days”).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Negative:</strong> the date is in the past (e.g., “42
                  days ago”).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This is useful for quick planning (“How many days until that
                deadline?”) or for understanding how far in the past a
                historical event occurred.
              </p>

              <h2>Quick mental method to estimate the day of week</h2>
              <p>
                You can approximate the weekday in your head using a simplified
                method:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Memorize the weekday for a reference date (e.g., 1 January
                  2000 was a Saturday).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Count full years between the reference year and your target
                  year, adding 1 day for each normal year and 2 days for each
                  leap year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Add the number of days from 1 January to your target date.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Take the total modulo 7 and shift from the reference weekday.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator essentially automates and generalizes this
                process, handling leap years and century rules for you.
              </p>

              <h2>Common questions</h2>
              <h3>Does the calculator handle leap years correctly?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. For the Gregorian calendar, a year is a leap year if it is
                divisible by 4, except years divisible by 100, unless they are
                also divisible by 400. For the Julian calendar, every year
                divisible by 4 is a leap year.
              </p>

              <h3>Why might historical sources disagree with the result?</h3>
              <p>
                Historical records sometimes use local calendar conventions or
                reflect the exact date when a region switched from Julian to
                Gregorian. If you are working with a specific country and era,
                check which calendar was in use and whether any days were
                skipped during the transition.
              </p>
            </section>

